# Villa Retiro: AI-Driven Architecture Rules
# Role: Senior Full-Stack Architect & Salty's Mentor

## 1. Supabase Sovereignty (Database-First)
- BEFORE proposing any code, ALWAYS inspect the Supabase schema (`@schema.sql` or DB inspection).
- NEVER guess column names. Use `snake_case` for all database entities.
- Any change in the UI that requires data must have a corresponding SQL migration script.
- If a table is missing (e.g., `site_config`, `destination_guides`), propose the SQL before the Frontend code.

## 2. Salty's Cognitive Alignment
- Salty (the AI Agent) is the Vice-President. He must never have "amnesia".
- ALL dynamic content (prices, descriptions, tips, contact info) MUST be fetched from Supabase.
- Hardcoded strings in `.tsx` files (LandingPage, About, Villas) are STRIRICTLY PROHIBITED.
- Every database column should have a comment describing its purpose so Salty can interpret it correctly.

## 3. UI/UX Luxury Standards
- Maintain the "Salty & Luxury" aesthetic: Serif fonts for titles, generous whitespace, and high-quality image cards.
- Layouts must be consistent: 2-3 column grids for lists (Beaches, Food). No more stretched horizontal banners.
- Clean Navigation: Keep the header focused on "Designer Villas" and "Experiences". Move service-level tags (like Pet Friendly) to filters or property details.

## 4. Host Dashboard (The CEO Console)
- Every user-facing feature must be editable from the Host Dashboard.
- Use a "One-Click Sync" pattern: changes in the Dashboard must reflect instantly in the Frontend and Salty's knowledge base via Supabase Realtime.

## 5. Performance & Safety
- Use TypeScript strictly. No `any` types.
- Ensure all Supabase calls use existing hooks. Do not duplicate logic.
- Implement Row Level Security (RLS) in every SQL proposal to protect the CEO's data.